    <section xml:id="ss-AccProcedure"><title>Procedure</title>

        <introduction>
                <p><alert>Materials</alert>: An aluminum track, a low-friction cart, computer interface with PASCO Capstone<m>^{\rm tm}</m> software, a sonic motion sensor, a small steel ball.</p>

                <p>You should notice that the subsections in this section parallel the subsections in <xref ref="ss-AccAnalysis" text="title" />.</p>
        </introduction>

        <subsection xml:id="sss-FlatTrack"><title>Cart and Flat Track</title>
        <aside><title>Note</title> <p>The Pasco Capstone interface is also used in <xref ref="c-Newton" text="type-hybrid" />, <xref ref="c-friction" text="type-hybrid" />, and <xref first="c-energy-1" last="c-energy-2" text="global">Labs</xref>.  You should start becoming familiar with the hardware and software.</p></aside>
        <p>Log into the computer (so you can save your data to your network drive) and then open Pasco Capstone.
        (<xref ref="s-capstone" text="type-global" /> will provide some instructions for setting up the software and connecting the equipment.)
        Connect the motion sensor to the computer interface.
        Set the data rate of the motion sensor at <m>50 \unit{Hz}</m>.
        Place a steel ball on the track and adjust the leveling screw at one end of the track to see if the ball rolls one way or the other.
        This will roughly level your track.
        Place the sensor about 20 cm from the end of the track, because this is the minimum distance detected by the sensor.
        (You might need to use the <q>sail</q> for the sensor to see the cart.)</p>

        <p>Place the cart on the track.  Capstone, via the sonic ranger, can measure the position and velocity of the cart as a function of time.
        (This is explained in <xref ref="s-capstone" text="type-global" />.)</p>
